-- Enrichment marathon batch: Knock, KnowledgeOwl, Koala AI, Kodi, Koel, Koha, Koillection, Komga

-- ── Knock ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Knock is a notification infrastructure platform that gives engineering teams APIs and a workflow builder to send email, SMS, push, chat, and in-app notifications.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (paid plans from $250/month)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Brooklyn, New York, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Knock Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Knock is a notification infrastructure API for developers. See how Knock's workflows, pricing tiers, and features compare to Courier, Novu, and OneSignal.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Knock is a notification infrastructure platform, sold as a hosted API and workflow engine, that lets product and engineering teams add multi-channel notifications, in-app inboxes, and customer messaging to their applications without building delivery logic from scratch. The company was founded in January 2021 by Sam Seely and Chris Bell, who had previously worked together as product and engineering leaders at Frame.io, where they experienced first-hand how painful it is to build and maintain notification systems as an application scales across email, SMS, push, and in-app channels. Knock is headquartered in Brooklyn, New York. The company raised a previously undisclosed 6 million dollar seed round led by Afore Capital, followed by a 12 million dollar Series A in February 2024 led by Craft Ventures with participation from Afore Capital and Preface Capital, bringing total disclosed funding to roughly 18 million dollars. Architecturally, Knock sits between an application's backend and its various delivery providers (Twilio, SendGrid, Postmark, Slack, and similar services): developers define reusable notification workflows, multi-step, multi-channel messages with conditional branches, delays, batching and digest logic, and per-recipient preference checks, either through a visual workflow builder in the Knock dashboard or in code, then trigger those workflows from application events or webhooks. Knock ingests recipient and object data from data warehouses, CDPs, reverse-ETL tools, and direct API or webhook calls, and lets teams model custom objects so that notification templates can be personalized dynamically at send time. The platform ships official SDKs for eight backend languages (Node, Python, Ruby, Go, Java, .NET, Elixir, and PHP), plus frontend components for building notification feeds and inboxes, a CLI that integrates with AI coding tools such as Cursor and Claude Code, environment-based version control with rollback for workflows, and built-in observability so teams can trace and debug individual message deliveries. Newer additions include an AI-assisted workflow builder that can draft a multi-step messaging journey from a single prompt, AI-generated and brand-customized email templates, and 'guides', targeted in-app messages such as banners, modals, and tooltips, which are also usage-metered. Knock reports processing hundreds of millions of messages per month for more than 200 companies, including Vercel, Webflow, Medium, Clay, Discogs, and Amplitude, and advertises 99.99 percent uptime along with HIPAA, SOC 2, GDPR, and CCPA compliance. Pricing follows a three-tier, usage-metered model. The free Developer plan costs 0 dollars per month and includes 10,000 messages, 500 monthly active guide users, and 500 AI agent credits, alongside unlimited workflows, broadcasts, channels, team members, and recipients. The Starter plan costs 250 dollars per month and raises the included volume to 50,000 messages and 2,500 guide active users at lower per-unit overage rates, and adds the ability to remove Knock branding from emails plus email client preview testing. The Enterprise tier uses custom, volume-based pricing and unlocks per-customer branding and preferences, translation and internationalization support, HIPAA compliance with a signed BAA, SAML 2.0 single sign-on, and a shared Slack channel with priority support. Usage-based overage charges are billed in arrears on the following month's invoice across all tiers. Knock is aimed primarily at software engineering and product teams at B2B SaaS and marketplace companies that need to ship reliable, cross-channel notifications quickly rather than build and maintain their own delivery, templating, preference-management, and retry infrastructure in-house; it is less suited to marketers running large-scale campaigns without engineering involvement, since Knock is fundamentally a developer-first, API-driven platform rather than a drag-and-drop marketing automation tool. Its closest direct competitors are Courier, another developer-focused notification-infrastructure API with similar workflow concepts, and Novu, an open-source notification infrastructure project that companies can self-host as a free alternative to Knock's hosted service. Knock also competes at the edges with broader customer engagement platforms such as Braze and Customer.io, which offer notification sending as part of much larger campaign and analytics suites aimed at marketing teams, and with raw delivery providers like Twilio, SendGrid, and OneSignal, which handle transport for a single channel but leave workflow orchestration and preferences for the customer to build. Knock's differentiation rests on combining a hosted, reliability-focused delivery layer with a developer-friendly workflow and data model, version control, and observability tooling purpose-built for engineering teams shipping notification features inside a product.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '146cfaaf-aaff-451e-bc9c-ee8099f69750';

