-- ── Koillection ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Koillection is a free, open-source, self-hosted web app for cataloging and organizing personal collections of any kind, from books to stamps to games.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Koillection Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Koillection is a free, self-hosted, open-source app for cataloging any type of collection. See its features, tech stack, and how it compares to CLZ Collectorz.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Koillection is a self-hosted web application for cataloging personal collections, created by developer Benjamin Jonard, with its public GitHub repository first created in May 2018 and released under the permissive MIT license as free, open-source software. It is designed for hobbyist collectors who want a dedicated system to organize and track physical collections of essentially any type, working conceptually like a nested file and directory system: users create top-level collections, for example books, stamps, vinyl records, action figures, or trading cards, and then add individual items inside them, each with custom fields, images, notes, and metadata. Technically, Koillection is built on the Symfony PHP framework combined with API Platform to provide a full REST API backend, paired with a Vue.js-driven frontend, and it functions as a Progressive Web App, meaning it can be installed on a phone or tablet home screen and used much like a native mobile app, including offline-capable behavior. Self-hosting the application requires a PHP environment together with a database of MySQL 8.0 or later, MariaDB 10.0 or later, or PostgreSQL 10.0 or later, and the project provides official Docker images to simplify deployment on home servers, NAS devices, or VPS instances, making it a common addition to homelab and self-hosted-app stacks. A deliberate design choice is that Koillection does not ship with built-in metadata scrapers for specific catalogs, such as automatic ISBN lookups for books or barcode databases for other collectibles; instead it lets users build their own custom scrapers against its REST API or enter metadata manually, trading some out-of-the-box convenience for flexibility and a lighter core application. Feature-wise, Koillection supports an unlimited number of collections and nested sub-collections, rich custom item-level metadata fields including text, numbers, images, and choice lists, tagging that works across different collections so related items can be grouped regardless of which collection they belong to, wishlists for tracking desired items, loan and missing-item tracking through a signs system, a night and dark mode theme, multi-user accounts with independent private collections per user, and granular sharing controls that let a user expose specific collections publicly or to specific people via shareable links. Because the application runs entirely on infrastructure the user controls, all data, images, and metadata remain on the user's own server rather than a third-party company's cloud, which is a core selling point for privacy-conscious collectors who do not want an inventory of potentially valuable items sitting on a commercial platform's servers. There is no company, subscription, hosted SaaS offering, or paid tier behind Koillection: it is maintained as a community open-source project on GitHub, with user-interface translations crowdsourced through the Crowdin platform, and every user self-hosts and maintains their own independent instance for free. Koillection's target audience is hobbyist collectors across categories like books, comics, stamps, coins, toys, and trading cards, home archivists cataloging a personal media library, and self-hosting or homelab enthusiasts who already run a Docker-based home server and want a dedicated, private inventory application rather than relying on spreadsheets, generic note-taking apps, or a commercial SaaS cataloging tool. Its closest competitors are the CLZ, or Collectorz.com, family of cataloging applications, including Book Collector, Comic Collector, and Movie Collector, which are commercial, per-category desktop and cloud products that include built-in barcode scanning and metadata lookups but charge licensing fees and are closed source; Delicious Library, a paid macOS-only cataloging application; and general-purpose productivity tools like Notion or Airtable, which some collectors repurpose as makeshift collection databases despite lacking a purpose-built collection, item, and tag data model. Koillection differentiates itself from the CLZ product family primarily by being entirely free, self-hosted, and general-purpose across any type of collectible rather than sold per-category with recurring or one-time licensing fees, while trading away CLZ's built-in barcode scanning and commercial metadata databases in exchange for complete control over one's own server, data, and privacy.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c742a777-74f7-4981-aabd-5b21669059f3';

